<br>
I grew up in a dedicated Teamsters home.  Mom and Dad were both teamsters.  That meant that we spent about 2-4 months out of every year on strike, on average... whether it was because my parents local contract was up or because their local was supporting the brotherhood somewhere else.<br>
<br>
Soooo, for 8 months of the year they got to work less and reap the benefits of union membership.  The rest of the time we got to juggle bills, sell off our posessions and do everything we could, often not successfully, to stay off welfare.  All the while, non-union truckers and support workers got paid.  It sure appeared to me that the union existed to extract dues from its members without providing anything substantial in terms of support - except to maintain the jobs of the lazy sacks who SHOULD be fired but can't be because of the union, and to completely prevent pay based on merit.<br>
<br>
Unions may have had a purpose at one time... a purpose for which we can probably all be thankful.  But I feel very confident saying that their heyday has past, and they do far more harm than good.  Certainly they did nothing but make my life miserable.  I wouldn't piss on a union leader if he was on fire.<br>
